However, universities still lack the policies and capacity to effectively manage and utilize this technology.

Generative artificial intelligence (GenAI) is becoming a familiar tool in higher education . An international survey conducted by the online learning platform Coursera with 4,200 lecturers and students in five countries—India, Mexico, the United States, the United Kingdom, and Saudi Arabia—showed that over 95% of participants had used AI in their studies or academic work.

The results show that attitudes towards AI are generally quite positive. Approximately 81% of faculty and students believe that AI enhances the educational experience. Notably, 80% of students reported an improvement in their grades after using AI, with 35% saying the improvement was significant.

However, AI has not completely replaced traditional learning methods. The majority of students reported using AI for less than half of their learning tasks. This suggests that AI primarily plays a supporting role, helping learners access information more quickly and personalize the learning process.

Faculty members are also increasingly applying AI in their work. Approximately 71% of faculty members reported regularly using AI to design lectures, assign homework, draft student correspondence, or manage time. Some even use AI to grade assignments or create exam questions.

However, according to the survey, 56% of participants believe that the current higher education system is not adequately prepared for the rapid development of AI.

One of the biggest problems is the lack of clear policy. Only 26% of faculty reported that their university had issued formal regulations regarding the use of AI. Without specific guidance, students and faculty are unsure what constitutes acceptable use and what violates academic rules.

This raises concerns about integrity in education. Approximately 65% ​​of survey participants believe that the unchecked use of AI could undermine the value of university degrees. Additionally, 37% are concerned about cheating and plagiarism, 37% worry that AI reduces human interaction in the learning environment, and 35% are concerned about the security of personal data.

The survey also revealed that many instructors lack confidence in their ability to use AI. Only 25% believe they and their colleagues have the necessary skills to effectively apply AI in the classroom, and only 27% believe they can detect AI-generated content. Meanwhile, AI technology is developing at a very rapid pace, making it increasingly difficult to control or keep up with the changes.

Experts argue that the solution is not to restrict AI, but to build a strategy for integrating this technology into education. This includes enacting clear policies, training faculty and students in AI skills, and redesigning assessment methods to suit the new learning environment.

Dr. Marni Baker Stein, Content Director at Coursera, commented: “Students are now ahead of universities in exploring how to use AI. Learners are increasingly aware of how to leverage this technology to support their learning process in a more flexible and personalized way.”

